s offer clues to intertwined human and natural histories that shape our planetary futures. In this era of aggressive hydrocarbon extraction, extreme weather, and severe economic disparity, how might certain objects make visible the uneven interplay of economic, material, and social forces that shape relationships among human and nonhuman beings? Future Remains is a thoughtful and creative meditation on these questions. The fifteen objects gathered in this book resemble more the tarots of a fortuneteller than the archaeological finds of an expedition—they speak of planetary futures. Marco Armiero, Robert S. Emmett, and Gregg Mitman have assembled a cabinet of curiosities for the Anthropocene, bringing together a mix of lively essays, creatively chosen objects, and stunning photographs by acclaimed photographer Tim Flach. The result is a book that interrogates the origins, implications, and potential dangers of the Anthropocene and makes us wonder anew about what exactly human history is made of.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHuman ecology. 0aNature and civilization. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aClimate Change.  aEnvironmental Justice.  aExtinction.  aWunderkammern.1 aArmiero, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmiero, Marco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarroll, Trisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmett, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmett, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarmer, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanwahr, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarkness, Ra